<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1882-01-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1882-01-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="36" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d36">
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                    <head>No. 36.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to <gloss type="to">Consul at
                                Panama</gloss>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1882-01-04"><hi rend="italic">January</hi> 4,
                            1882</date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p>Mail following to Trescot:</p>
                    <p>President seeks to extend friendly offices impartially to both republics.
                        Exert pacific influence. Avoid issues leading to offense. The Calderon
                        affair and its surroundings can be attended to here.</p>
                    <p>When you come home, we prefer that you do not return by Buenos Avres.</p>
                    <closer><signed>FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>